There are quasi-periodic patterns in solar and stellar flaring energy releases. Often the EM radiation generated in flares shows a pronounced oscillatory pattern, with characteristic periods ranging from a fraction of a second to several minutes, or even longer in the case of stellar superflares. These are referred to as quasi-periodic pulsations (QPPs) to emphasise that they often contain apparent amplitude and period modulation. QPPs have been detected in all EM bands (including radio, microwave, white-light, Hα\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$\upalpha $\end{document}, UV, EUV, soft X-ray, hard X-ray and gamma-ray) and occur in all stages of the flare. QPPs are detected across multiple instruments, so they are not an instrumental effect, and are observed in a significant fraction of flares. This review paper is primarily a theoretical modelling review and details the possible physical mechanisms underpinning QPPs, with an emphasis on the physical processes that generate the resultant range of periodicities.

